    private static int value = 42;

    public static void M()
    {
        var fn = ref readonly int () => ref value;  // error CS0518
    }
}
```

What's happening?

data.content:
These are two distinct issues:

---

**Case 1 — `left && right` with `dynamic`**

The `&&` operator is never directly overloaded — it desugars into `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`, all of which must exist on the **same type**. Your `IFilter` defines `true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**. Only `CompositeFilter` has all three.

In older C# versions, when one operand was `dynamic`, the compiler deferred all checking to runtime. C# 15 now validates at compile time that the static type of the left operand has the full operator set (`&`, `true`, `false`) — even when the other operand is `dynamic`. Since `IFilter` lacks `operator &`, this is rejected.

**Fixes:**
```csharp
// Option A: Add operator & to the interface
interface IFilter
{
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
}

// Option B: Make both operands dynamic
var combined = (dynamic)left && right;
```

---

**Case 2 — `ref readonly` lambda with `var`**

```csharp
var fn = ref readonly int () => ref value;
```

CS0518 ("predefined type not defined or imported") means the compiler recognizes this syntax but can't find a required BCL type needed to synthesize the delegate. Natural type inference (`var`) for `ref readonly`-returning lambdas requires a new predefined type in the target framework. This typically indicates a **SDK/runtime version mismatch** — your compiler supports C# 15 but the referenced `System.Runtime` is older.

**Fixes:**
```csharp
// Option A: Verify your TFM and restore packages
// Ensure <TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework> and run dotnet restore

// Option B: Declare the delegate type explicitly (avoids natural type inference)
delegate ref readonly int RefReadonlyFunc();
RefReadonlyFunc fn = () => ref value;
```
